This code snippet is intended to parse an order string and calculate the total price of the items ordered. However, it contains a potential security risk due to the use of `split("\\s+")` without proper validation or sanitization. The `split("\\s+")` method splits the input string into an array based on whitespace characters, which can lead to unexpected behavior if the input string contains special characters or punctuation.

To mitigate this risk, it is recommended to use a regular expression that matches only alphanumeric characters and spaces. Here's an improved version of the code:

```java
import java.util.List;

public class OrderProcessor {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String orderString = "123–apple–$50";
        List<String> priceList = Arrays.asList("apple", "banana", "cherry");

        // Use a regular expression to split the input string
        String[] orderData = orderString.split("\\s+");

        if (orderData.length != 3) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid order format");
        }

        String productDetails = orderData[0];
        int productPrice = priceList.indexOf(productDetails);

        if (productPrice == -1) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Product not found in price list");
        }

        int orderPrice = Integer.parseInt(orderData[1]) * productPrice;

        System.out.println("Total price: $" + orderPrice);
    }
}
```

In this improved version, we use a regular expression `\\s+` to split the input string into an array. We also add validation checks to ensure that the input string has exactly three parts and that the product details exist in the price list. This approach helps prevent security vulnerabilities related to splitting strings based on whitespace characters.

