 public void foo(int i) {
 switch (i) {
 case 1:
 if (true) {
 break;
 }
 }
 }
}

content:
This code snippet defines a method `foo` within a class named `Example`. The method takes an integer parameter `i`. Inside the method, there is a `switch` statement that checks the value of `i`. If `i` equals 1, it enters a nested `if` block. However, the `break` statement inside this `if` block does not terminate the execution of the `if` block but rather continues to the next case in the `switch` statement. This behavior is known as "fall-through" and can lead to unexpected results if not handled carefully.

To avoid fall-through, you should use a `return` statement after the `break` statement inside the `if` block. Here's how you can modify the code:

```java
public class Example {
    public void foo(int i) {
        switch (i) {
            case 1:
                if (true) {
                    return; // This will terminate the execution of the method
                }
            default:
                break;
        }
    }
}
```

By adding `return;` after the `break` statement, the method will exit immediately when it encounters the value of `i` equal to 1. This prevents fall-through and ensures that the rest of the code in the `switch` block is not executed.

